title: Object to a limited company being struck off

heading_context: Object to a limited company being struck off
chunks.html_content:
You can object to a limited company being struck off the Companies Register if:

  • you are a shareholder or other interested party, such as a creditor
  • you have a reason to stop the company being removed from the register - for example, you have a legal claim against them or they owe you money

You can only object after notice that the company is going to be struck off has been published in The Gazette.

You must have evidence to support your objection - for example, invoices or other evidence showing the company owes you money.

chunks.html_content: You can withdraw your own company’s application to be struck off if you’re a director.

heading_context: Object to a limited company being struck off
If the company has already been struck off
chunks.html_content: If the company has already been struck off, you’ll need to apply for a court order to restore a company instead. You can only do this in certain circumstances - for example, if they owed you money when they were dissolved.

If the company has already been struck off, you’ll need to apply for a court order to restore a company instead. You can only do this in certain circumstances - for example, if they owed you money when they were dissolved.

heading_context: Object to a limited company being struck off
chunks.html_content:
To object online you need:

  • the limited company number of the company that is being struck off - get information about a limited company
  • your supporting documents in a digital format (these must be images, Microsoft Excel, Microsoft Word or PDF files)

Your supporting documents must:

  • be less than 6 months old
  • clearly show the full name of the company, including the correct name ending - for example ‘limited’ or ‘ltd’
  • support your reason for objecting, for example invoices proving the company owes you money
  • be less than 4MB in size

You must object within 2 months of the date of the notice in The Gazette.

You must have a Companies House account to make an objection online. You can create an account before you start if you do not have one.

Make an objection

If you cannot object online, send your objection by email or post.

You must object within 2 months of the date of the notice in The Gazette. If you’re sending your objection by email or post it must arrive 2 weeks before this deadline to be processed in time.

heading_context: Object to a limited company being struck off
chunks.html_content: Call Companies House if you have a disability that prevents you from emailing or posting your objection. You’ll have one month to arrange for someone to email or post supporting evidence for you.
chunks.plain_content:
Object to a limited company being struck off
If you have a disability
Call Companies House if you have a disability that prevents you from emailing or posting your objection. You’ll have one month to arrange for someone to email or post supporting evidence for you.

heading_context: Object to a limited company being struck off
chunks.html_content:
Companies House will let you know if your objection is successful. If it is, the company will not be struck off for another 6 months.

Tell Companies House before this deadline if you either:

  • need more time, for example to complete legal action against the company
  • resolve your issue with the company and no longer object to it being struck off

If you want more time, Companies House will ask you to prove that you’ve made progress towards resolving your issue. For example, if the company owes you money and you have simply sent another invoice, Companies House is unlikely to extend the deadline. If you’ve started legal action to recover a debt they may do.

If you do not contact Companies House before the time limit and the company still meets all the conditions to be struck off, it will be struck off.
